post_text:
The New York State Public High School Athletic Association (NYSPHSAA) announced today that football, volleyball and competitive cheer fall seasons will be postponed until March 1, 2021 to address membership concerns associated with high-risk fall sports. The decision was rendered by the elected NYSPHSAA officers late this afternoon. Low and moderate risk fall sports, meanwhile, are still authorized to begin practices on September 21, 2020 as previously announced.

Student-athletes that were planning to play Girls Volleyball are permitted to play another fall sport that Fillmore offers and still play Volleyball in March.. AS noted our Volleyball season will now begin March 1 of 2021.

This year FCS is partnering with The Rural Outreach Center to provide winter apparel (coats, snow pants, boots) for families within the FCS community.

If you are interested in participating in the program this year, you must contact the ROC at (716)240-2220 ext. 101 by September 25th. This is in place of the Warm Your Children Program that FCS has used in the past.

FCS will pick up your orders from ROC and will distribute later October/early November. You will be contacted via phone closer to the pick-up date.

If you have questions, feel free to call Miss Bailey at 567-2270 or text 716-244-7705.

Thank you!

In a summer like no other, we have partnered with the Ralph Wilson Foundation and Project Play of WNY to distribute free PlayPacks throughout Allegany and Cattaraugus counties. The play packs will include a rubber playground ball, tennis ball, jump rope, frisbee, sidewalk chalk, bubbles, and state of play activity card deck.

post_text:
Jared Emmons is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. Jared’s favorite memories are any of Mr. Heaney’s stories and Mr. Rust’s classes in general. Jared is proudly enlisting in the US Army National Guard, that he calls a family. Jared says he wouldn’t be able to do that without the help of his older brother.

Jared’s teachers had wonderful things to say about him. Ms. Brown said, “I’m proud of how focused and committed Jared is to his future and his pursuits of the National Guard.”

Mr. Heaney added, “Jared Emmons is an honorable person. I love Jared’s sense of duty and service. He will go on to make the world a better place.”

post_text:
Ford Hamilton is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. Ford will always remember the caring teachers he had at FCS. Ford will be joining the workforce after graduation.

Mr. Vosburg said, “There is so much more than meets the eye with Ford. Someone who doesn't know him might mistake his quiet demeanor for lack of participation. However, after teaching Ford, I know he is a thinker who accomplishes the tasks that he sets his mind to.”

Mr. Witkowski added, “Ford rarely speaks, but when he does, people listen. For what he says is full of deep, insightful, caring, and accurate thoughts. I always appreciated what Ford was able to do in class along with his subtle generosity.”

Our senior spotlight today is on Phil Hess. Phil is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. While at FCS, Phil participated in basketball and golf. He will be remembered at FCS for being the MVP on our first sectional golf team. After graduation, Phil will be entering the work force.

Phil’s teachers had wonderful things to say about him. Mr. Parks said, “Phil is one of the most talented golfers we have had at FCS! He is a great kid and always fun to be around.”

Miss Lyman added, “Phil has always been a respectful kid. He is a leader in his own unique way and has the self-confidence to be himself.”

post_text:
Kameron Mills is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. Kam has participated in basketball and was the Vice-President of the Class of 2020. Kam will always remember the many friends he made at FCS. He will be attending the University of Northwestern Ohio after graduation.

Kam’s teachers had wonderful things to say about him. Mrs. Coon said, “Kameron was a such a fun kid to have in class. He was always able to rattle off random and fun science facts! Walking down the hall, Kameron always had a smile and such a warm greeting to give. It has been so nice to watch Kam mature and grow into a nice young man.”

Mr. Heaney added, “Fillmore will miss Kam Mills. He has a larger than life presence that makes people laugh. Kam is certainly one of a kind and I’ll miss hearing about how he’s not meant for facts.”

Today’s spotlight is on Zach Olver. Zach is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. While at FCS, Zach participated in golf. Zach will be remembered at FCS for being a part of our first sectional championship golf team. After graduation, Zach will be entering the work force.

Zach’s teachers had great things to say about him. Mrs. Heaney said, “Zach is such a good guy. Over the years of teaching him, he has always been pleasant, helpful and fun to discuss life with. I know he will do great things!”

Mr. Witkowski added, “Zach is a hidden gem. He is a person that “runs under the radar,” never calling attention to himself, but always getting things done. Zach is highly dedicated to his friends, but is willing to do anything, for anybody when needed.”

Our spotlight today is on Corrin Roth. Corrin is graduating with a Regents Diploma. While at FCS, Corrin participated in track and choir. She will be remembered at FCS for her sense of humor. Corrin will be attending Elizabeth City State University.

Corrin’s teachers had great things to say about her. Mrs. Coon said, “It has been a joy watching Corrin grow into such an independent and thoughtful young lady. Corrin is hard working and knows how to make you laugh. She's so well rounded and an inspiration to her peers.”

Mrs. Ellsworth added, “Corrin was so much fun to have in class. She always tried to be so straight-faced and serious but I could put a smile on her face. I really enjoyed being her teacher in class and in driver education.”

Today’s spotlight is on Samantha Wilcox. Samantha is graduating with a Regents Diploma. While at FCS, Samantha participated in FFA and worked numerous hours in her part time job. Her great work ethic and FFA participation will be remembered at FCS. Samantha will be attending Alfred State for Agriculture.

Samantha’s teachers had wonderful things to share about her. Mr. Heaney said, “Sammy Wilcox is a sweetheart. She is kind and caring and just a really great human being. I’m very proud of her.”

Mr. Witkowski added, “Sam has a calm dedication. She was easily one of the most dedicated students in Earth Science, who always made sure her work was done and done well. However, her most important trait was her calm, friendly demeanor to work enthusiastically with others and help bring them up-to-speed.”

Our spotlight today is on Emma Bower. Emma is graduating with a Regents Diploma with Advanced Designation. While at FCS, Emma participated in tennis, track, NHS, and FFA. She experienced success at FCS reaching tennis sectionals and in FFA contests. Emma will be attending Alfred State to major in Agricultural Business.

Emma’s teachers had great things to say about her. Mr. Nolan said, “Emma always came to play. She is a real gamer and a team player. She is one of the best players I’ve had the pleasure to coach. Her teammates love her, and the opposing coaches thought the world of her. Emma is a great representative of Fillmore Central School.”

Mr. Witkowski added, “Emma is an enigmatic scholar. When Emma put her mind to things, she did great things in class and on the tennis court. Her understanding, insights, and explanations of Earth Science concepts were always among the best in her class.”

Today’s spotlight is on Gaven Thompson. Gaven is graduating with a Local Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. While at FCS, Gaven participated in track. Fun creek adventures with Mr. Hunter in 7th grade and fun at field days were his favorite FCS memories. Gaven plans on entering the work force to pursue a career as an Autobody Technician.

Gaven’s teachers had wonderful things to say about him. Mr. Witkowski said, “Gaven shows quiet determination. When tackling difficult tasks, Gaven brings the skill set of courage few people see or realize. He doesn’t bring a lot of attention to himself, but Gaven is steady, and always gets the job done.”

Mrs. Herman added, “Gaven you are a marvelous young man. You have overcome many challenges and keep setting goals for yourself without looking back. I have seen you grow into a man in pursuit of his dreams. I'll never forget your cooking skills either!”

Nick Freeman is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. Nick participated in wrestling and Drama Club. His favorite memory of FCS is his entire time in Mr. Mast’s class. Nick has enlisted in the United States Navy and leaves July 16th.

Ms. Brown said, “I really enjoyed seeing Nick step outside his comfort zone this year and join the musical for the first time. I am also so impressed with his drive and dedication in working towards a future in the Navy.”

Mr. Witkowski added, “Nick is a future leader. During his time at Fillmore, Nick was hands-down the friendliest student at Fillmore as he had a smile and greeting for everyone. I am pleased to see how Nick has developed his self-confidence this year and am looking forward to seeing Nick excel in his leadership skills as he serves our country in the Navy.”

Jaydin Wolfer is graduating with a Regents Diploma. Jaydin has participated in soccer, track and basketball. Her favorite memory of FCS is winning sectionals in soccer. Jaydin plans on getting certified as a Phlebotomist after graduation.

Jaydin’s teachers had wonderful things to say about her. Mr. Witkowski said, “Jaydin shows persistent dedication. Jaydin has made a huge impact on Fillmore Central School by serving as a model to never give up-- whether on the field or in the classroom. Her dedication as a student and athlete will be missed next year.”

Mr. Fuller added, “When most people would walk away or give up when faced with adversity, Jaydin would meet things head on and fight through, no matter how much it may have hurt her physically. She is an example of perseverance and dedication to anyone and everyone.”

Will Valentine is today’s senior spotlight. Will is graduating with a Local Diploma with a Technical Endorsement. While at FCS, Will participated in basketball. All of the success the team had was his favorite memory. Will plans on entering the work force to pursue a career in Auto Body.

Will’s teachers had great things to say about him. Mr. Crouch said, “Few FCS students have grown and matured more than Will Valentine over the past few years. It was a privilege to coach Will, and to watch him grow not only as a basketball player, but as a young man. Will’s determination and leadership will be missed on the basketball team, but will help him be successful in the workplace next year!”

Mrs. Wagner added, “You have come so far since Middle School, a boy with spunk and wit. It has been wonderful watching you gain momentum growing into a young man full of vigor and passion for athletics and accomplishing so much more than you knew was possible. Good luck in your future Will, we are proud of you!”

Cortney Beardsley is graduating with a Regents Diploma. Cortney has participated in tennis, Drama Club and track while attending FCS. Her favorite memories from her time at Fillmore are the great conversations she had with Mr. Mullen, Mr. Heaney, and Mr. Nolan. Cortney plans on joining the work force and moving out of NY State after graduation.

Cortney’s teachers had great things to say about her. Ms. Brown said, “Cortney is the perfect blend of spunky attitude and kind-hearted sweetness. She stands up for what she believes in, is always herself and cares about and sticks up for others. I’m so glad she was a part of the musical this year. During rehearsals when Cortney would walk on the stage as her character Mae “Mama” Peterson I liked to look around the room at her cast mates because everyone was watching her with huge smiles on their faces.”

Mrs. Hannon added, “Few people can truly be their authentic selves and unapologetically express themselves the way you do. Keep being you and keep shining!”

Paige Johnson is graduating with a Regents Diploma. While at FCS she participated in volleyball and basketball. Her favorite memories of FCS were the feeling of being together with her friends and the great friendships she made. She also loves how the teachers and everyone is so helpful and always knows what is best for you. Paige plans to attend Genesee Community College for Liberal Arts and Sciences.

Paige’s teachers had great things to say about her. Mrs. Thompson said, “Paige Johnson always has a smile and a good morning or hello when she walks by.”

Mrs. Heaney added, “Paige, I will miss all of the time you have spent in my classroom over the last few years. I just never knew when you would pop in (and possibly stay for the whole period), but I loved every second of it! You always know how to crack me up, and you were always super helpful to both me, my children and my students. Thank you for always being willing to help me out in whatever way I might need both inside of school and out. I wish you the best!”

post_text:
Coaches Appreciation Day

The Fillmore Central School Athletic Department would like to recognize and thank our Varsity, JV, Modified, and Assistant Coaches for all their physical, emotional, and social investment into the athletic programs at FCS. This year we had 29 dedicated coaches at FCS that served in some capacity. They combine for over 300 years of coaching experience that includes coaching over 600 different teams. This has allowed them to leave an impact on over 1000 student-athletes over 38 years. We can’t thank you enough for everything you do to make FCS Athletics the success it is today!

Our senior spotlight today is on Madison Engler. Madison is graduating with a Regents Diploma with Advanced Designation. While at FCS, Madison participated in NHS and track and field. Her favorite memory of FCS was being warmly welcomed into a new school for her last two years of high school. She made friends that she will never forget. Madison received an Allegany County Foundation Scholarship and plans on attending SUNY New Paltz for International Business.

Madison’s teachers had great things to say about her. Mr. Crouch said, “Maddy is a rare student. She combines a thoughtful, sensitive personality with an incisive intellect. I’ve immensely enjoyed the chance to get to know her and be challenged by her critical thinking. Best of luck to Maddy as she is destined to be a leader in the future!”

Mrs. Hannon added, “Madison, you are a true leader, a thinker, a problem solver and a trailblazer. Keep being yourself and change the world!”

Her favorite memories of FCS are every dairy judging trip with Mrs. Nickerson and their team. Abby has received a destination scholarship from SUNY Cobleskill where she will major in Dairy Production and Management.

Abby’s teachers had wonderful things to say about her. Mr. Parks said, “Abby is an outstanding athlete, and even better friend! She never stops giving her best in all that she does.”

I suspect very few teachers could come up with anything but positive comments when asked about Abby Hatch.”

Abby has received a destination scholarship from SUNY Cobleskill where she will major in Dairy Production and Management.

Abby’s teachers had wonderful things to say about her. Mr. Parks said, “Abby is an outstanding athlete, and even better friend! She never stops giving her best in all that she does.”

Mr. Vosburg added, “Abby is a great person who cares about those around her. She works hard for all of the success that she earns, a work ethic that is no doubt a result of the responsibilities that come with growing up on her family-owned farm. I suspect very few teachers could come up with anything but positive comments when asked about Abby Hatch.”

post_text:
Fillmore Athletics Sportsmanship Recognized

The Allegany County Athletic Association recently announced that Fillmore C.S. Athletics were the overall Sportsmanship winner for the 2019-2020 school year. All varsity sports are considered, with our athletes, coaches and spectators being evaluated. During the year Girls Soccer and Girls Basketball were ranked #1 overall and all our teams finished in the top half. Congratulations to FCS and everyone that made an impact.

Today the spotlight is on Daniel Colter. Daniel is graduating with a Local Diploma. While at FCS Daniel was a member of the soccer team. His favorite memory was all the crazy fun he had in class with Mr. Heaney. Daniel plans on joining the work force right after graduation and later going to Finger Lakes Community College for film and photography.

Daniel’s teacher had great things to say about him. Mrs. Brown said, “Dan looks tough on the outside but has a marshmallow heart on the inside. He is sweet, kind and good. I’m glad to have had him as a student.”

Mrs. Heaney added, “Dan, I will never forget when you first came to Fillmore school. I have watched you grow from the shy, timid “new kid” to an outgoing, positive and hard-working individual. I am so happy to see you with your friends in the hall and on stage with the musical. Your charisma makes me smile. Over the years I have spent being your teacher we have had many talks, but the one thing I will never forget is the day we made you a pink paper mustache to wear... just because!”

Luke is graduating with a Regents Diploma with Advanced Designation. Luke has participated in soccer, basketball and tennis at FCS. He was a County All-Star for basketball during 10th, 11th and 12th grade. In addition to athletics Luke participated in Drama Club, Student Council and was Vice President of the Awards Committee. Luke’s favorite memory of FCS was playing on all the great sports teams that we have had. Luke plans on attending Houghton College to major in Sports Management.

Luke’s teachers had high praise for his character. Mr. Heaney said, “Luke is one of the sweetest and nicest young men to ever pass through the halls of FCS. His kindness and compassion are truly inspiring to anyone lucky enough to know him.”

Mrs. Ellsworth added, “Luke has always been a sweet kind soul. No matter where I see him he always has a pleasant attitude and is kind to all around him. He is a perfect example of what true grace looks like.”

Brandon is graduating with a Regents Diploma with a CTE endorsement. He plans on attending college in the field of Computer Information Systems. His favorite memory of FCS was Mr. Heaney reading tweets provided by Kameron Mills.
Mr. Witkowski described Brandon as always smiling.

“Having a bad day? A visit from Brandon can be the cure. His genuine concern for others and willingness to strike up a conversation made him an admirable person to collaborate with in class. It has been great to watch his confidence grow as both a person, and as a student from when he was a sophomore to now as a graduating senior.”

Mrs. Wagner said, “Brandon, I have seen you grow leaps and bounds into a wonderful, hardworking, young man. When you came out of your shell you showed us what amazing things you could accomplish. I look forward to seeing what else you have to offer the world!”

post_text:
Kainan Beardsley is graduating with a Regents Diploma. Kainan is an active member in the FFA and participated in baseball and wrestling. His favorite memory of FCS was going to Nationals with the FFA Dairy Judging Team. Kainan plans on attending SUNY Morrisville for Animal Science.

Mr. Witkowski described Kainan as, “Constantly dependable. Even in tough times, Kainan is always willing to work hard when others would simply quit. It doesn't matter whether it is in the classroom, or on the wrestling mat, Kainan is there every day trying to make the most of his opportunities. His ability to get along with everyone, and willingness to work with anybody make him an extremely valuable member of the Class of 2020.”

Miss Brandt said, “Kainan is hilarious. You can always count on him for the perfect comment at the perfect moment. He is also (maybe secretly) one of the kindest kids I’ve gotten the privilege to know. Oh, and have you seen him judge a cow?!”

This is an important update from Fillmore Central School.

First, the governor extended his executive order to keep schools closed until and including April 28th.

Second, Regents exams have been cancelled this year. We have been provided little information regarding how this will play out but the state has assured us that further guidance will be available soon.

Finally, we will continue delivering meals this week with one small change. For this week only, both Thursday and Friday's meals will be delivered on Thursday.

We will continue to update you as the information is provided. Please let us know if there is anything we can help you with. Our staff continues to work hard to help you through this unfortunate event.

post_text:
Good evening. This is an important message from Fillmore Central School. Earlier today the governor extended his order to close schools from April 1st to April 15th. Our teachers will continue instruction with the current plan, if there are any changes we will update you immediately. We will also continue delivering meals to those who have signed up for them. In order to protect our staff we are asking those of you with a driveway longer than 100 feet to put a tote at the end of your driveway. We are also asking those of you with a driveway less than 100 feet to place a tote near your door to respect social distancing rules and remember to keep your dog tied up or in the house between 10 o'clock and 1 o'clock. The staff has been instructed to not deliver meals to homes with loose dogs. We appreciate your cooperation in helping keep our staff safe. If you have any questions or need anything just let us know, we are here to help all of you. Have a good weekend.

Michael Dodge
Superintendent
Fillmore CSD

post_text:
While we are closed for instruction at Fillmore Central School, we are still able to provide breakfast and lunch to any of our students in the district upon request. Lunch will be available to be delivered to your residence or to be picked up at school in the drop off loop on Lowell Street between the hours of 10:00 and 1:00. When receiving your lunch, you will also receive breakfast for the following day. A Fillmore staff member will deliver the meals to your car, please do not get out of your vehicle.

If you are interested in this service, please contact Heidi Rose at (585) 567-2270 or hrose@fillmorecsd.org with the following information:

-The names of your children.
-The grade level of each student.
-Whether you are planning on picking up the food in the drop off loop or would like it delivered to your house.

By providing this information, you are requesting to receive breakfast and lunch on weekdays for the duration of the closure. This service will start this Thursday March 19th and will continue until we return to school.

This message is to let you know that your administration is taking the COVID-19 virus very seriously and the safety of our students, staff and community is the primary focus. The administration team is working with public health officials and area leaders throughout the day today and we will be sending all updates out through this system later this afternoon. If you do not have your email up to date in Power School you will be able to find these updates on our web page and Facebook page. Thank you for your cooperation during this difficult and fluid situation.

post_text:
Raising a Strong and Healthy Baby – Week 3

This will be the last bit of advice on this topic…for now!
• Language and Bonding: Hold and talk to your baby while feeding him/her.
o Why?
 This is a great time to get to know each other.
 Talking to your baby will help him/her become better at talking, reading, and writing later in life.
 If the bottle is propped, milk will pool up in the baby’s mouth and lead to eventual tooth decay.
Happy parenting! Be on the lookout for more Break Through tips soon.

post_text:
Fillmore FFA wins big at Districts and qualifies for Sub-States!

All 14 Fillmore FFA members that competed at the NYSFFA District 10 Leadership Development Event have qualified to move on to the Sub-State Contest on March 14.

Results were as follows…

1st Place in Parliamentary Procedure: Easton Cahill, Abby Hatch, Emily Hatch, Haylee Holmes, Harley Miller, & Ada Sylvester

1st Place in Prepared Public Speaking: Zoe Beardsley

2nd & 3rd Place in Extemporaneous Public Speaking: Yanely Cristino & Kyle Paulsen

4th Place in Employment Skills: Easton Cahill

1st through 5th Place in People in Agriculture: Karmen Frazier, Luke Colombo, Damon Wood, Ben Beardsley, & Kristina Wilcox

Saturday is the big day!! Come on out to BCS for our alumni basketball games between Fillmore and Belfast! Admission is $3 per person or $7 per family (3 or more). The girls kick it off at 6:30 with the guys to follow at 8:00. IT'S NOT TOO LATE TO BE A PARTICIPANT! There will be raffles and contests throughout each game so bring some cash! All proceeds go to benefit a Fillmore family in need and BCS Girls basketball. Come on down for a great night of fun for a good cause!
